b:["$","div",null,{"className":"prose","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Who Should Choose Which?"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The ideal user for each platform differs considerably. HubSpot Operations Hub is best suited for HubSpot users, revenue operations, sales teams, making it a strong choice if you fall into any of these categories. Make (Integromat), meanwhile, shines for power users, agencies, complex automations, which means it may be the better pick if your needs align with those use cases.\n\nFounded in 2006, HubSpot Operations Hub describes itself as \"Operations automation platform within HubSpot for data sync and workflows.\" Make (Integromat), established in 2012, positions itself as \"Visual platform for designing, building, and automating complex workflows.\" With 6 years between them, HubSpot Operations Hub brings the maturity and proven track record of a veteran platform, while Make (Integromat) offers the fresh perspective and modern architecture of a newer entrant."}]]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"verdict-box","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Our Verdict"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"After analyzing all the data, **Make (Integromat)** comes out slightly ahead in this comparison, thanks to higher user ratings (9.0 vs 7.0), more features (10 vs 9), availability of a free plan. However, this does not mean HubSpot Operations Hub is a poor choice — far from it. HubSpot Operations Hub excels in its own right, particularly for HubSpot users and revenue operations.\n\nOur recommendation: if you value superior visual workflow builder, go with Make (Integromat). If deep hubspot crm integration matters more to you, HubSpot Operations Hub is the way to go. Either way, both are solid platforms that have earned their place in the market."}]]}]
